BLACK MESA SECURITY COMPLEX, WAREHOUSES


Sam, the elevator spat us out. Not into offices, not into labs, but right into the heart of the Black Mesa war machine. The security complex. A place where H.E.C.U.s feel, if not at home, then like a heavily fortified barracks, where every corner is under fire, every door is monitored, and every intruder is simply target number three.

We're greeted by a large warehouse. Enormous. Shelves soar upward, crates piled high, with narrow passages between them that turn into deadly corridors if someone with a machine gun is lurking at the other end. The complex also has utility beams, cranes, and catwalks. There's probably someone there too.

Situation: We're on the lower level. Ahead is a warehouse labyrinth. Beyond it is the exit to the surface, to the landing pad. But you can't just walk through. There are a lot of H.E.C.U.s here. They've taken up positions, set up checkpoints, and somewhere in the depths, judging by the sound, automated turrets are working. Smart little things that never tire and never miss.

Our goal: reach the control room on the surface. From there, disable the turrets and open the door to the bunker. Because the door is locked. Of course it's locked. Because someone decided we got through the previous floors too easily.

Control console. Disabling the turrets and opening the door to the bunker is our primary objective. Everything else is secondary. As soon as the door opens, run there without looking back.

Battle outside. Don't get involved. Humans are fighting aliens, and that's fine. While they're busy with each other, we slip to the console, do our thing, and disappear into the bunker.
